Support Vector Machines

Dani Bauer

In this tutorial, we discuss Support Vector Machines and demonstrate their implementation in R. We first consider their performance in a simulated example. We then use them in our case study examples, analyzing whether they can improve on the learners considered so far.

rm(list=ls())
#install.packages("e1071")
#install.packages("ggplot2")

Let’s again define:

TPR <- function(y,yhat)  { sum(y==1 & yhat==1) / sum(yhat==1) }

Support Vector Machines

Review of Concepts and Maths

The intellectual starting point for SVMs is that: \[ f(x) = \beta_0 + \beta_1\,x_1 + \beta_2\,x_2 + \ldots + \beta_p\,x_p = 0 \] defines a hyperplane, and we can define a binary linear classifier according to \[ f(x^{(0)}) \begin{array}{c} >\\<\end{array} 0, \] (where points fall relative to that hyperplane). We can determine a hyperplane that maximizes the distance to the two classes, allowing for exceptions. It turns out that only a few points where the distances are sharp or that are exceptions matter, these are called support vectors.

This idea generalizes to non-linear functions \(f(\cdot)\): \[ f(x) = 0 \] defines a boundary, and we can classify according to \[f(x^{(0)}) \begin{array}{c} >\\<\end{array} 0.\] SVMs use kernel functions to define non-linear \(f\)’s that work particularly well.

Setup

We start out by setting the scene: We set a seed and we load various packages. The package e1071 is the where the SVM functionality is provided (so you may have to instal it). In addition we load packages that allow us to illustrate the data and packages to run comparisons.

library(ggplot2)
library(e1071)
library(MASS)
Warning: package 'MASS' was built under R version 3.5.2
set.seed(3)

Let’s consider some arbitrary predictors in two-dimensional space, \(x_1\) and \(x_2\):

x_1 <- 2 * rnorm(100)
x_2 <- 2 * rnorm(100)

As we discussed above, the equation \(f(x_1,x_2) = 0\) fixes a boundary in the two-dimensional space, so the “true” classification may be done according to: \[ f(x_1,x_2) \;\; \begin{array}{c}>\\< \end{array} \;\; 0. \] We rely on the example that was used in generating the (non-linear) plot from lecture:

y_true <- factor(sign(5 * sin(0.5 * (x_1 - 2)) + 2 - x_2))
mydata_true <- data.frame(y_true,x_1,x_2)
ggplot(mydata_true) + geom_text(aes(x_1,x_2,label=y_true,colour=y_true))

To generate more realistic data sets, where the classification is not sharp along the boundary, let’s add noise. We consider two different examples, one with less noise – labeled 1 – and one with more noise – labeled 2.

y_1 <- factor(sign(5 * sin(0.5 * (x_1 - 2)) + 2 - x_2 +  1 * rnorm(100)))
mydata_1 <- data.frame(y_1,x_1,x_2)
ggplot(mydata_1) + geom_text( aes(x_1,x_2,label=y_1,colour=y_1))

y_2 <- factor(sign(5 * sin(0.5 * (x_1 - 2)) + 2 - x_2 +  3.5 * rnorm(100)))
mydata_2 <- data.frame(y_2,x_1,x_2)
ggplot(mydata_2) + geom_text( aes(x_1,x_2,label=y_2,colour=y_2))

Simulated Example I: Well-Separated Classes

Let’s start out with the first example, where there is little noise such that the classes are well-separated. Let’s run our first SVM classifier (see the package e1071 for more details):

svm_1_rad <- svm(y_1 ~ . , data = mydata_1, kernel="radial", gamma=1.0, cost=10)
#Other kernel options are linear, polynomial, radial, sigmoid
summary(svm_1_rad)

Call:
svm(formula = y_1 ~ ., data = mydata_1, kernel = "radial", gamma = 1, 
    cost = 10)


Parameters:
   SVM-Type:  C-classification 
 SVM-Kernel:  radial 
       cost:  10 
      gamma:  1 

Number of Support Vectors:  30

 ( 15 15 )


Number of Classes:  2 

Levels: 
 -1 1
table(svm_1_rad$fitted, y_1)
    y_1
     -1  1
  -1 58  2
  1   2 38
table(svm_1_rad$fitted, y_true)
    y_true
     -1  1
  -1 59  1
  1   5 35

One has to choose a kernel, a gamma parameter that is associated with the kernel (the higher, the more non-linear), as well as a cost parameter. All are tuning parameters. Here, the gamma was chosen to roughly optimize the predictions (relative to the “true” data set), so some tuning was done. In this case, the number of support vectors is relatively low (30).

We observe that the SVM does very well, the misclassification error is only 6%.

Let’s compare to Quadratic Discriminant Analysis (QDA):

qda_1 <- qda(y_1 ~ ., data = mydata_1)
pred_qda_1 <- predict(qda_1, mydata_1)
table(pred_qda_1$class, y_1)
    y_1
     -1  1
  -1 53  5
  1   7 35
table(pred_qda_1$class, y_true)
    y_true
     -1  1
  -1 53  5
  1  11 31

Clearly QDA does not work as well in that it is not able to capture the pattern well. On the other hand, a very flexible learner may overfit the data. Hence, the SVM seems to be doing a nice job: It allows to capture the pattern but, at the same time, is sufficiently “simple” so that, when tuning appropriately, over-fitting can be mitigated.

Simulated Example II: Poor Separation

Now let’s look at the second data set where the data is less well-separated. Let’s again fit the SVM, using the same choices (after all, the “true” pattern is the same):

svm_2_rad <- svm(y_2 ~ . , data = mydata_2, kernel="radial", gamma=1.0, cost=10)
summary(svm_2_rad)

Call:
svm(formula = y_2 ~ ., data = mydata_2, kernel = "radial", gamma = 1, 
    cost = 10)


Parameters:
   SVM-Type:  C-classification 
 SVM-Kernel:  radial 
       cost:  10 
      gamma:  1 

Number of Support Vectors:  60

 ( 31 29 )


Number of Classes:  2 

Levels: 
 -1 1
table(svm_2_rad$fitted, y_2)
    y_2
     -1  1
  -1 61 17
  1   1 21
table(svm_2_rad$fitted, y_true)
    y_true
     -1  1
  -1 63 15
  1   1 21

With 16%, the error rate is substantially larger, and the number of support vectors is significantly greater (60).

Let’s compare to QDA:

qda_2 <- qda(y_2 ~ ., data = mydata_2)
pred_qda_2 <- predict(qda_2, mydata_2)
table(pred_qda_2$class,y_2)
    y_2
     -1  1
  -1 55 18
  1   7 20
table(pred_qda_2$class,y_true)
    y_true
     -1  1
  -1 64  9
  1   0 27

Hence, while for QDA the in-sample error is higher than for the SVM classifier (25% vs. 18%), the “true” error is lower for the QDA (9% vs. 16%). Thus, at least in this example, QDA outperforms the SVM.

Hence, it appears that SVM is doing particularly well in the first context where the classes are well separated.

Case Study I: Caravan Insurance Purchases

Let’s go back to the Caravan insurance data:

library(ISLR)
data(Caravan)
dat <- Caravan
dat$Purchase <- I(dat$Purchase=="Yes")*1
X <- scale(dat[,1:85])
tst <- 1:1000
X.trn <- X[-tst,]
X.tst <- X[tst,]
Y.trn <- dat[-tst,86]
Y.tst <- dat[tst,86]
train <- dat[-tst,]
test <- dat[tst,]

xvars <- names(dat)[-86]

As a reminder, the lasso-logistic regression model achieved by an AUC of 0.7456.

K-Nearest Neighbor

Let’s first consider the k-nearest neighbor (knn) approach, where the predicted class at a point \(x_0\) is chosen based on the \(k\) points that are closest: \[ y(x_0) = \max_j\left\{\frac{1}{K} \sum_{i \in N_K(x_0)} 1_{\{y_i=j\}}\right\}, \] where \(N_k(x_0)\) denotes the index set of the \(K\) points in the training sample that are closest to the point \(x_0\) (usually in the sense of Euclidean distance).

Let’s try:

library(class)
set.seed(1)
pred.knn.1 <- knn(X.trn, X.tst, Y.trn, k=1)
table(pred.knn.1, Y.tst)
          Y.tst
pred.knn.1   0   1
         0 873  50
         1  68   9
TPR(Y.tst, pred.knn.1)
[1] 0.1168831
pred.knn.3 <- knn(X.trn, X.tst, Y.trn, k=3)
table(pred.knn.3, Y.tst)
          Y.tst
pred.knn.3   0   1
         0 920  54
         1  21   5
TPR(Y.tst, pred.knn.3)
[1] 0.1923077
pred.knn.5 <- knn(X.trn, X.tst, Y.trn, k=5)
table(pred.knn.5, Y.tst)
          Y.tst
pred.knn.5   0   1
         0 930  55
         1  11   4
TPR(Y.tst, pred.knn.5)
[1] 0.2666667
pred.knn.10 <- knn(X.trn, X.tst, Y.trn, k=10)
table(pred.knn.10, Y.tst)
           Y.tst
pred.knn.10   0   1
          0 941  59
          1   0   0
TPR(Y.tst, pred.knn.10)
[1] NaN

So while it is not immediately clear how to obtain class probabilities as for the previous learners, we can identify some potential purchasers by simply mimicking similar observations.

SVM

Let’s start with the SVM, where we use cross validation to determine the accuracy. Since it takes a while to run each fit, rather than using a tuning routine, let’s perform a manual search:

#Again, these take a while.  Consider limiting the number of covariates if it takes too lonng (e.g. only some PAY variables)
mod_svm_1 <- svm(default ~ LIMIT_BAL +  AGE + PAY_0 + PAY_3 + BILL_REC + BILL_AVG + PAY_AMT1 + PAY_AMT2 + PAY_AMT3 + PAY_AMT4 + PAY_AMT5 + PAY_AMT6, data = train, kernel="radial", gamma = 0.5, cost=1, cross=5)

So here the SVMs also do not seem to be competitive, although they get closer. In particular, for low specificity levels the SVM seems to be competitive.

Overall:

  • SVMs are flexible classifiers. Various choices for the kernels are possible, and the parameters are sufficiently transparent to allow for relative straightforward tuning.

  • SVMs work particularly well if the classes are well separated. In this case relatively few support vectors are necessary and the boundaries are well-identified.

  • SVMs appear to be competitive classifiers – they offer a reasonable compromise between allowing for complexity and stability that works well in various situations.
